\cite[Conjecture 1.2]{clvgrassmannian}
    Let $X$ be a general rational curve of degree $e$ in $G(k, n)$, where without loss of generality we take \(k \leq n-k\).
Then $N_{X/G(k, n)}$ is balanced if and only if either \(e = 1\) or none of the following occur:
\begin{itemize}
\item The degeneracy exceptions: We have \(e < n-k\) and \(e \neq k\).
\item The characteristic \(2\) exceptions: The characteristic is $2$ and \(k = 1\) and \(e \not\equiv 1\) mod \(n-k - 1\).
\item The tangent bundle splitting exceptions: We have $q_1+ q_2 \leq (k-r_1)(n-k-r_2)$ and \(r_1 r_2 \neq 0\).
\end{itemize}

